node.text: Across the US, 79.8% of ICU beds are in use — and almost a third are occupied by Covid-19 patients, according to data from the US Department of Health and Human Services. Eight states had more than 90% of their adult ICU beds occupied Sunday: Alabama, Georgia, Texas, Arkansas, Florida, Mississippi, Nevada and Kentucky.

node.text:
The US Military Academy at West Point will finally unveil a new monument dedicated to the Buffalo Soldiers, a group of Black soldiers who played a key role in the westward expansion of the US. The Buffalo Soldiers taught riding skills at the academy for 40 years.⁠
⁠
"This monument will ensure that the legacy of Buffalo Soldiers is enduringly revered, honored and celebrated while serving as an inspiration for the next generations of cadets," said US Military Academy 60th Superintendent, Lt. Gen. Darryl A. Williams.⁠
⁠
(📸: Jackie Molloy/ The Washington Post/Getty Images)

node.text:
A nurse in Colorado took empty Covid-19 vaccine vials and made them into beautiful art, paying tribute to her fellow health care workers. "I had noticed all these hundreds and hundreds of empty vaccine vials that were otherwise going to be wasted, and I thought they were just really beautiful and wanted to do something significant and meaningful with them," nurse Laura Weiss said.⁠
⁠
(📸: Laura Weiss)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNN on September 05, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and text that says 'CNN In Afghanistan, some girls live as boys to taste freedom "Bacha posh," which in Dari means girl "dressed up as a boy,' is an ancient tradition rooted in inequality. This allows a girl to have a boy's freedoms sport and traveling alone outside the home. like playing In areas where an education is only offered to boys, she can go to school and receive an education. "This is society where boys and men have almost all the rights," said author Jenny Nordberg.'.

node.text:
In order to reach for what we think of as some very basic human rights, an Afghan girl can put on a pair of pants, cut her hair off and pass as a boy, said Jenny Nordberg, author of "The Underground Girls of Kabul." This practice could become much riskier, but at the same time perhaps even more relevant, Nordberg said, as women face discrimination under the Taliban.⁠
⁠
Tap the link in our bio to learn more about this tradition.

node.text:
